												<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Arcavian wrote:<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Frodlin wrote:<BR>
<DIV>If the named mobs in KodTaz/Yxxta were toned down a little bit, one of the Malevolant priests in Ikkinz 2 trial&nbsp;were made fully slowable, then things would be just about perfect.</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>While I agree with Frodlin, doing this will trivialize it for a Warrior. Right now its tough for a Warrior, and Hard for a Knight. With doing the above, it will become average to a Warrior, and tough for a Knight. It needs to stay tough for both, and that is the hardest part, without some form of sacrifice. <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<P>I've often wondered about this logic, because it makes no sense.&nbsp;&nbsp; You know how a lot of people said that stunning mobs that didn't need to be stunned produced no tangible benefit to outweigh the drawbacks?&nbsp;&nbsp; Well, the drawbacks of popping a discipline are FAR greater than the drawbacks of casting a stun (which you'd ordinarily be casting anyhow for aggro purposes).</P>
<P>What I'm getting at is that if mobs dont' "require" discs, then we don't use them for the most part, regardless of triviality or not, I'm not gonna use a disc that hoses me for 10 minutes if I *need* it at that point.&nbsp;&nbsp; Thus the whole "trivialises it for warriors" argument against making mobs not require a disc is a little off, if they dont' require discs, we simply don't use them.</P>
																																		<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 100; overflow: hidden;">
														<p><img src="http://members.roadfly.org/Fearsons/frodsig.gif" height=110 width=300>
							</div>
																
